I live about a block away in the same complex at ashley park lane.  I find this store is very convenient for me when I need a couple of things and I don't mind the prices. The store is very clean and the shelves are very neat. I also find some of the brands interesting because I have never seen them before and I try them out sometimes. I am learning to venture out more and open up my world a little bit. I shop at Aldi for the big bulk paper products, meats, fish, fruits and vegetables. When I need to get something specific I can always find it at Harris Teeter or Compare. I am originally from NY and have been here over a year now. What I find interesting about Whole Foods is the interaction with the staff. Half the staff is nice and friendly and customer centric. If you are looking for a product they will let you know where it is located, if they changed it to another aisle, or if they are out and what stores near-by may carry it. I find this is a plus because it is a sign of a good company and a well trained staff. The other half looks annoyed to be there, and act like they are suffering through some kind of punishment. Sometimes I look at them in the eyes and they avoid any kind of interaction. A simple and friendly hello would be enough for me. This is what I call a friendly light place and maybe it is a Charlotte thing. They are polite but they really don't want any kind of interaction with other people. I get it because that is how NY people are. We are are always in a rush to catch a train, bus, or cab to and from work and the people that get in our way are just annoying. I know this is a rough job market, but why on earth would you take a job dealing directly with the public if you don't really enjoy being around people.

A  young caucasian male walks up and one of the ladies immediately asked him if he needed assistance and even came from behind the counter to assist him. My facial expression was noticeable, then I  was acknowledge. I did say to one of the young ladies,  that neither of them asked me if I needed help. She was apologetic and  the saleslady that was eager to help the male customer stated,  "I'm sorry, I did not see you walk up." That is the wrong thing to say. That is what is said to all persons of color when they are not given fair customer service in the same situation.  These young ladies seem nice enough, and maybe it was not intentional, but they need to be mindful. Sadly,  that unfair treatment  amongst people of color happens way too often, and it is time for it to stop. This is a review of a catered, Thanksgiving dinner; ordered online and picked up at the store: Not wanting to chance a restaurant interior in this pandemic environment, we'd taken the recommendation of a respected friend and ordered the Thanksgiving meal package  (small whole turkey, dressing, mashed potatoes, green beans, gravy, and cranberry sauce). We knew it  was designed for  four people; but, we figured the leftovers would be good through the weekend.  We were extremely disappointed in most respects. The mashed potatoes and dressing were inedible. They never made it to the table. God only knows how long they'd been sitting in their refrigerated containers; but, it left them in a very sorry state. The green beans and gravy were extremely under-seasoned, and the small, precooked turkey was so cold that it took over 2 hours to heat to the recommended temperature.  Throughout the experience, the phrase "live and learn" kept coming up for me. On this, the day after, it's been replaced by "never again."

If this is a policy Whole Foods is adopting regarding their food/hot bar and other food sections, it should be made much more widely known and aware to the public and customers. And of course the staff there exhibited no sign of emotion or care to even explain to us what's available and what's not available. Extremely disappointing and cold environment.  EDIT: After having reached out to Whole Foods and settling this issue with them, I can speak to the great deal of quality customer service this store strives for. Not only was I explained the situation in a well-rounded matter as well as receiving empathy for my subpar experience, I was also given compensation for my troubles which was far and beyond my expectation. I'm happy to live near a grocery store that truly care about the community it serves.

As far as Whole Foods go, this one is a cute little quaint location that packs a lot into a small space.  It is paid parking in the attached garage and has a nice indoor dining area as well as outdoor patio seating. They even have a little couch and cushy chair sitting area and a bar where you can order beers on tap and coffee.  They have a hot bar and sandwich bar and pizza by the slice as far as their eat-in or to-go food offerings go.  I didn't really grocery shop, but they have a decent, though small, beer & wine section. I was a little disappointed they don't offer bombers and their rose section was definitely lacking. Apparently, though, one of the employees said we weren't the first to complain about them not carrying bombers of beer and that he's petitioning store management to start off with a small area of them. So, Mgmnt, if you read these reviews, please look into carrying at least a small cache of high abv bombers #kthanks.  Another thing to keep in mind for this location is that it is located at the bottom of a newly constructed apt bldg and apparently they are having all kinds of construction issues that keep setting off the fire alarm. Sitting at the bar on a gorgeous, but hot, Saturday afternoon the alarm went off 3 bites into my slice of pizza and we were forced to evacuate the bldg...pizza & drink in hand (thank goodness I didn't order a beer like my date, which he had to leave in the store because we couldn't have it outside!). It took like 20mins before they started letting people back in and after talking to a regular who was standing outside w/us, this happens about once a week, if not more. My date decided to forfeit his beer (even though I told him that Whole Foods totally owed him a new one, but he didn't want to bother) so we could continue w/our day as I had finished my pizza while standing outside, uncomfortably in the heat.  Needless to say, I won't be coming back to this location for a while until the alarm thing is fixed because that was NOT at all an enjoyable experience!

I primarily worked with Maddie, and she was so patient and helpful. We met in person initially, and I was able to taste test a few options. The staff there that day was such a pleasure to work with! I wish I had their names to give them kudos as well! But shortly after our initial meet and greet, all of my communication with Maddie was by email. She replied so quickly to every concern I had. She offered suggestions and made creating the perfect meal smooth and simple. I can't tell you how much a bride needs smooth and simple in preparing for her big day! So thank you to Whole Foods, the catering department, and Maddie. You made my "Best Day Ever" even better!!

Once you shop Whole Foods and Trader Joe's going back into a Harris Teeter/Kroger is sheer drudgery. Whole Foods has amazing staff and you never have to check yourself or bag your own groceries. I have taken items back that I didn't like the taste of and I get a full refund with no questions. The staff always bags beautifully and will even carry out your groceries. You will never have to wonder an isle- there is always someone in each department that will proactively ask you "are you finding everything okay." Shop the sales and you will not pay more that Kroger/Harris Teeter. I have found that I generally paid more for organic produce at Harris Teeter even when it was on sale.
Love it

Me and Whole Foods kind of have a love/hate relationship. It's a great store to go and hang out in, and they have some great selections, but it's so pricey. Even when I went shopping with coupons, I only saved around $10 and spent more for a week's worth of groceries than I usually spend for 2 week's worth at Trader Joe's. But, I do love their coffee bar - much healthier and better than Starbucks! And the hot bar is pretty good too. Just wish it wasn't so expensive.

I went to Whole Foods mostly for one reason and that was to buy makeup that I cant get anywhere else and test colors, etc. I went on a day I needed some groceries and I even wrote out a grocery list and printed out coupons. I ended up getting very few groceries because even on sale and with a coupon, prices are far too high. There is no need to spend double on organic, I can get the same quality elsewhere (or clean it). Even foods that are NOT organic are about 50% more. I must say that there are some things here you simply cannot get elsewhere that are perhaps worth the extra cost and time it would take to go to this store for those exclusive items. I also got some of their prepared food, which was really tasty and has great options. Overall, this store is overwhelming with options! Which I feel is good and bad. Usually, variety is a reason items at a store could cost more. But, of course variety makes things more interesting, they have just about everything you can imagine. Whole Foods has an ideal mission, a great atmosphere, and is obviously very popular.

The reason I shop at Whole Foods is to get the products I like that are not available anywhere else. Well it turns out selling other peoples products is not  good enough for companies like Wingman's or Whole Foods anymore. The temptation to make even more money by selling your own products (Whole Foods 365) seems to great to resist. Slowly all the products are being replaced by the Whole Foods 365 brand. No more choice, Whole Foods will decide what is the best for us and just stop carrying the things we like. I have already seen it happen with a few of the items that I would stop in there to purchase. I mentioned this to a girl at the check out and she told me that the 365 brand products are much less expensive. I don't shop at Whole Foods to save money. If I wanted to do that I could go to many other lower end grocery stores. I saw this same thing happen to Wingman's in the Northeast years ago and it too bad it happening to While Foods too.

When they didn't have many Vegan options available in the cold deli section we asked if they had any falafel in the back, they said no and we went on bummed. Then a gentleman came up to us, Jim and he offered to have them make us a fresh falafel sandwich with the falafel they had from another product.  That's service! Freshly made and going one step further to please a customer is why I rate WH a 4. 5 if they would have a few more Vegan options available.  Thanks Jim!

This is definitely my favorite place to shop for groceries or bath products and honestly feel out of place anywhere else. The produce is amazing and ripe even in the winter months. They don't try and sell you something withered, moldy, and frost bit like Aldi, Harris Teeter, Sam's Club, and Food Lion. You can think when you go in that it's too fancy and expensive based on looks but it's honestly cheaper than anywhere else you go and the produce actually lasts until you're finished eating it. Please keep in mind that this is a natual store so they do not sell over the counter medication. They have tons and tons of alternatives that are better for your body. This Whole Foods has honestly changed my quality of life. Their return policy is AMAZING! You can eat half of something, not like it, and they'll give you your full money back. If you want your family to be healthy come stop by, please don't let anyone's opinions turn you away.
